The [Anti-terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001](/Anti-terrorism,_Crime_and_Security_Act_2001) is a piece of legislation enacted by the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom). It was formally introduced on November 19, 2001, a mere two months after the devastating [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks) in the United States. The Act received its [royal assent](/Royal_assent) and officially came into effect on December 14, 2001. It’s worth noting that a significant portion of this Act’s provisions weren't exclusively focused on terrorism, a fact that drew criticism from a Parliamentary committee regarding the compressed timeframe for such an extensive bill that included measures beyond immediate emergency concerns.

This legislation was not without its detractors. One commentator famously labeled it "the most draconian legislation Parliament has passed in peacetime in over a century," a stark assessment of its reach and impact. The repercussions of the Act were significant, culminating on December 16, 2004, when the [Law Lords](/Law_Lords) declared Section 23 to be incompatible with the [European Convention on Human Rights](/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights). Despite this ruling, under the framework of the [Human Rights Act 1998](/Human_Rights_Act_1998), the section remained in force until it was eventually superseded by the [Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005](/Prevention_of_Terrorism_Act_2005).

### [Long title](/Short_and_long_titles)

The [long title](/Short_and_long_titles) of the Act meticulously outlines its extensive scope: "An Act to amend the [Terrorism Act 2000](/Terrorism_Act_2000); to make further provision about terrorism and security; to provide for the freezing of assets; to make provision about immigration and asylum; to amend or extend the criminal law and powers for preventing crime and enforcing that law; to make provision about the control of pathogens and toxins; to provide for the retention of communications data; to provide for implementation of Title VI of the Treaty on European Union; and for connected purposes." This verbose description, while legally precise, hints at the wide-ranging implications of the legislation, extending far beyond the immediate response to terrorism.

### [Citation](/Citation_of_United_Kingdom_legislation)

The Act is formally cited as [2001 c. 24](/2001_c._24). It was introduced by [David Blunkett](/David_Blunkett), and its territorial extent covers the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), with specific exceptions for certain parts in [Scotland](/Scotland) and [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland). Parts 5 and 12, for instance, did not apply to Scotland, while section 100 was not applicable in Northern Ireland. Furthermore, sections 50–56 extended to the British Overseas Territories.

The Act received [royal assent](/Royal_assent) on December 14, 2001, and the majority of its provisions came into force on the same date, with some sections taking effect on July 7, 2002. It has since been amended by subsequent legislation, including the [Police Reform Act 2002](/Police_Reform_Act_2002) (2002 c. 30), the [Criminal Justice Act 2003](/Criminal_Justice_Act_2003) (2003 c. 44), the [Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005](/Prevention_of_Terrorism_Act_2005) (2005 c. 2), the [Terrorism Act 2006](/Terrorism_Act_2006) (2006 c. 11), and the [Immigration, Asylum and Nationality Act 2006](/Immigration,_Asylum_and_Nationality_Act_2006) (2006 c. 13). Related statutory instruments and legislation include S.I. 2001/3644, the [Proceeds of Crime Act 2002](/Proceeds_of_Crime_Act_2002) (2002 c. 29), S.I. 2002/1822, the [Crime (International Co-operation) Act 2003](/Crime_(International_Co-operation)_Act_2003) (2003 c. 32), and S.I. 2005/1071. The Act's status is marked as "Amended," with a revised text of the statute as amended available.

### Part 1 (Terrorist property)

This section of the Act, comprising Sections 1–3 and Schedules 1 and 100, directly targeted the financial dealings of suspected terrorists and their organizations. It effectively rewrote portions of the earlier [Terrorism Act 2000](/Terrorism_Act_2000), specifically those concerning the seizure of assets believed to be linked to terrorism. This was a crucial move, aiming to disrupt the funding mechanisms that fuel terrorist activities.

### Part 2 (Freezing orders)

Part 2 of the Act re-enacted and significantly expanded upon provisions originally found in the Emergency Laws (Re-enactments and Repeals) Act 1964, the roots of which could be traced back to the [Defence (General) Regulations 1939](/Defence_Regulations). This provided a legal framework for freezing assets under specific circumstances.

#### Usage against Iceland

A notable, and controversial, application of this part of the Act occurred in October 2008. Prime Minister [Gordon Brown](/Gordon_Brown) invoked it, through the [Landsbanki Freezing Order 2008](/Landsbanki_Freezing_Order_2008), to freeze the British assets of the Icelandic bank [Landsbanki](/Landsbanki) during the [Icelandic financial crisis](/Icelandic_financial_crisis). The justification provided was that the Treasury held a reasonable belief that "action to the detriment of the United Kingdom's economy (or part of it) has been or is likely to be taken by a person or persons."

It's important to emphasize that the short title of an Act, unless explicitly stated, does not inherently limit its powers. The Act, in this instance, did not specify that the "action to the detriment of the United Kingdom's economy" had to be terrorism-related. This distinction became critical, as the government had successfully resisted attempts during the Bill's passage through the House of Lords to confine Part 2 solely to terrorism-related cases. The Act's [long title](/Short_and_long_titles) itself lists "to provide for the freezing of assets" as a distinct objective from amending the [Terrorism Act 2000](/Terrorism_Act_2000) and making further provisions about terrorism and security.

The Icelandic Prime Minister, [Geir Haarde](/Geir_Haarde), vociferously protested this action, describing it as "a terrorist law... being applied against us" and an "unfriendly act." This highlights the broader implications and potential misapplications of such broad legislative powers.

### Part 3 (Disclosure of information)

This part of the Act granted new powers to [Her Majesty's Customs and Excise](/Her_Majesty%27s_Customs_and_Excise) and the [Inland Revenue](/Inland_Revenue) (which have since merged to form [His Majesty's Revenue and Customs](/His_Majesty%27s_Revenue_and_Customs)). These powers allowed them to disclose information for "law enforcement purposes." Additionally, it clarified existing requirements for disclosing information pertinent to criminal investigations, with a particular focus on confidential information held by public bodies.

### Part 4 (Immigration and asylum)

Part 4 introduced a highly contentious provision allowing the [Home Secretary](/Home_Secretary) to certify any non-British citizen suspected of terrorism and detain them indefinitely, even if deportation was legally prohibited. This measure was challenged by nine detained suspected terrorists, and on December 16, 2004, the [Law Lords](/Law_Lords) ruled against it, issuing a [declaration of incompatibility](/Declaration_of_incompatibility) with the [European Convention on Human Rights](/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights), as mandated by the [Human Rights Act 1998](/Human_Rights_Act_1998). The provision was effectively dismantled in March of the following year, during its scheduled review, and its powers were replaced by "[control orders](/Control_order)" introduced via the [Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005](/Prevention_of_Terrorism_Act_2005).

#### Implementation

The [Immigration Act 1971](/Immigration_Act_1971) already permitted the deportation of individuals deemed a threat to national security when insufficient evidence existed for prosecution. However, a ruling by the [European Court of Human Rights](/European_Court_of_Human_Rights) in the landmark case of [Chahal v United Kingdom](/Chahal_v_United_Kingdom) in 1996 stipulated that individuals could not be deported to a country where there were substantial grounds to believe they would face torture. The government argued that Part 4 was necessary to circumvent this legal and security quandary, enabling indefinite detention without charge or trial.

Recognizing that this measure potentially exceeded the bounds of [Article 5 of the ECHR](/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights), the government included section 30, which allowed for a derogation—an opt-out—from certain Convention obligations. This was justified under the claim of a "state of emergency threatening the life of the nation," a perspective arguably shaped by the unfolding [war on terror](/War_on_terror). The [Special Immigration Appeals Commission](/Special_Immigration_Appeals_Commission) was designated to oversee this process.

The derogation order came into effect on November 13, 2001, and was repealed on April 8, 2005. During this period, the government maintained that the United Kingdom was experiencing a [state of public emergency](/State_of_emergency) that threatened the life of the nation, as defined by [Article 15(1) of the ECHR](/ECHR_article_15). This part of the Act was renewed by Parliament on March 3, 2003, without a vote, and again on March 3, 2004, this time with a vote.

#### Cases

This section requires updating to reflect recent events or newly available information. (December 2016)

Between 2001 and 2003, sixteen foreign nationals were detained under these powers at [HM Prison Belmarsh](/HM_Prison_Belmarsh). The detentions occurred in waves: eight in December 2001, one in February 2002, two in April 2002, one in October 2002, one in November 2002, two in January 2002, and one in October 2003. An additional individual was certified but detained under separate powers. Of the total detained, two voluntarily departed the United Kingdom. As of November 18, 2003, the remaining fourteen were still in detention. A report from the Council of Europe dated July 23, 2004, indicated that in March 2004, fourteen individuals were certified as suspected international terrorists and deprived of their liberty in the UK. Twelve of these were held solely under Part 4 of the Anti-Terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001, with half of them having been detained since December 2001.

#### Appeals

The Act did establish a process for appealing to a judicial tribunal against the Home Secretary's detention decisions. However, the government contended that a specialized appellate process was necessary due to the sensitive nature of the evidence, which might compromise intelligence methods, operatives, and other individuals if disclosed. Consequently, the ATCSA established special evidentiary rules, most notably allowing for the exclusion of the detainees and their legal representatives from proceedings. To purportedly safeguard their rights, specially vetted "special advocates" were appointed. Nevertheless, there is evidence suggesting these special advocates faced difficulties in effectively representing their clients' interests, with two ultimately resigning following the House of Lords' December 2004 ruling.

In October 2002, the [Special Immigration Appeals Commission](/Special_Immigration_Appeals_Commission) upheld the lawfulness of the Home Secretary's derogation, affirming the existence of a "state of emergency threatening the life of the nation."

A series of legal challenges were brought against the powers and procedures established under the ATCSA. On December 16, 2004, the [Law Lords](/Judicial_functions_of_the_House_of_Lords) ruled that the detention powers under Part 4 of the ATCSA were incompatible with the UK's obligations under the European Convention on Human Rights. The Court, by a majority of 8–1, determined that the purported derogation was not justifiable under [Article 15 of the European Convention on Human Rights](/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights), as the measures could not be considered "strictly required by the exigencies of the situation." Furthermore, the Court found the measures to be discriminatory, contravening Article 14 of the Convention.

The ruling's core points can be summarized as follows:

*   No detention pending deportation had exceeded seven days, let alone three years, undermining the proportionality of the measure.
*   The law was unjustifiably discriminatory. It posed a hypothetical: what if a British citizen, also suspected of terrorism, required indefinite detention without trial? Such a scenario was not accommodated by the law.
*   There was no discernible state of emergency threatening the nation's life. Other European countries, having faced more severe crises, had not declared such a prolonged state of emergency, certainly not without public notice.

The Court quashed the derogation order and issued a declaration under section 4 of the [Human Rights Act 1998](/Human_Rights_Act_1998), stating that the ATCSA provisions empowering the preventative detention of non-British suspected international terrorists were incompatible with the European Convention. While a declaration of incompatibility does not automatically invalidate legislation, it carries significant moral and political weight, creating pressure for legislative reform.

#### Replacement of Part 4

In response to this ruling, Part 4 of the ATCSA was replaced by the [Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005](/Prevention_of_Terrorism_Act_2005) in March 2005. This new Act substituted indefinite detention with "[control orders](/Control_order)," which impose extensive conditions on the movements of suspected individuals, effectively approximating [house arrest](/House_arrest). A key difference is that the powers under the 2005 Act apply to both British and non-British suspected terrorists. At the time of its enactment, considerable debate surrounded its compatibility with domestic and international human rights laws. Eleven control orders were issued on the night the Act passed, targeting terrorist suspects scheduled for release. By October of the same year, however, only three remained in force.

### Part 5 (Racial hatred)

This part of the Act expanded the scope of criminal law concerning hate speech. It amended existing legislation by substituting the term "racially aggravated" with "racially or religiously aggravated" in certain contexts, thereby broadening protections against discrimination based on both race and religion.

### Parts 6–8 (Weapons of mass destruction)

These parts of the Act addressed the proliferation and use of weapons of mass destruction. They criminalized dealings in [biological](/Biological_agent) or [chemical weapons](/Chemical_weapon) and the detonation of a [nuclear explosion](/Nuclear_explosion). Furthermore, it became illegal to disclose information that could potentially compromise the security of any nuclear site or nuclear material.

### Part 9 (Aircraft security)

Part 9 empowered the Secretary of State to enact new regulations concerning aircraft security. It also provided for the detention of aircraft if there was suspicion of an act of violence against a person on board.

### Part 10 (Police powers)

This part enhanced police powers in specific areas. It authorized the police to forcibly obtain fingerprints and other identifying features from individuals to confirm their identity. Additionally, it permitted the [Ministry of Defence Police](/Ministry_of_Defence_Police) to exercise police powers outside their usual jurisdiction when dealing with non-MOD related crimes, under circumstances defined by the statute. Similarly, members of the [British Transport Police](/British_Transport_Police) were granted authority to operate as police officers beyond their "natural jurisdiction" (primarily the railways), again within specific statutory parameters.

### Part 11 (Retention of communications data)

This part of the Act established broad powers for the Secretary of State to regulate telecommunications companies and internet service providers. These regulations mandated the [retention of data](/Telecommunications_data_retention) for national security purposes, a measure that has been a subject of ongoing debate regarding privacy and surveillance.

### Part 12 (Bribery and corruption)

Part 12 extended existing laws against bribery and corruption. It covered cases where the functions of the individual receiving or being offered a reward had no connection to the United Kingdom and were performed outside the country. It also broadened the scope of corruption offenses, enabling prosecutions for acts that would constitute corruption if committed within the UK. The definitions for these corruption offenses were primarily found in the [Public Bodies Corrupt Practices Act 1889](/Public_Bodies_Corrupt_Practices_Act_1889) and the [Prevention of Corruption Act 1906](/Prevention_of_Corruption_Act_1906).

The [Serious Fraud Office](/Serious_Fraud_Office_(United_Kingdom)) initiated an investigation into the [Al-Yamamah arms deal](/Al-Yamamah_arms_deal) based on this strengthened legislation, an investigation that ran from late 2003 until December 14, 2006, when it was abruptly discontinued.

### Part 13 (Miscellaneous)

This part granted the Secretary of State the authority to implement the provisions related to [Police and Judicial Co-operation in Criminal Matters](/Police_and_Judicial_Co-operation_in_Criminal_Matters) as outlined in the [Maastricht Treaty](/Maastricht_Treaty).

### Part 14 (Supplemental)

This final part of the Act established the timetable for the review of the legislation by the independent reviewer of terrorism legislation, ensuring a mechanism for ongoing scrutiny and assessment.

